page.text: Growth has occurred rapidly in the City of Manassas, Virginia since
the late 1990’s, and with it, the development of over ninety percent
of the City. In 2002, the City adopted the 2002 Comprehensive
Plan to guide and sustain growth in the area, and, in 2008, initiated
the Manassas Next – 2030 Comprehensive Plan process. The 2002
Comprehensive Plan designated six study areas within the City of
Manassas, which included the Prince William Hospital System
Campus and Sudley Road Study Area (also referred to as Study Area
1). For this sector area, the 2002 Comprehensive Plan envisioned a
strong, regional hospital system and support services; Sudley Road
as a well-maintained road complete with sidewalks, landscaping and
organized vehicular access and movement; and higher-density offi ce
buildings with professional and health-related businesses.
Sudley Road, as it is known today, has existed since before the Civil
War and once served as the major northern route to Sudley Springs
and Catharpin. Prior to the construction of the Prince William
Hospital in 1964, there was no major development north of Grant
Avenue. Following the development of the hospital, however, the
Post Offi ce, several offi ce and commercial centers, and multiple
churches were constructed along Sudley Road. Additionally, the
existing residential communities surrounding this area continued to
develop well into the 1960s. Today, Sudley Road serves as a gateway
The Sudley Road corridor has traditionally remained a commercial/
retail corridor that is supported not only by the hospital, but by a
large medical-offi ce component that serves residents of the City and
the surrounding Prince William County. Over the years, the Prince
William Hospital has expanded several times to provide additional
medical services and stay competitive in a growing healthcare market.
In late 2009, the Prince William Hospital merged with Novant
Health, a not-for-profi t, integrated healthcare system with facilities
primarily in Virginia, North Carolina and South Carolina. The new
Novant-Prince William Hospital team is in the process of completing
a master plan for the Prince William Hospital, concurrent with this
sector planning process, which will likely include future plans for
hospital expansion and provision of services.
The following goals and objectives were identifi ed for the Prince
William Hospital System Campus and Sudley Road Study Area in the
• Expand the hospital into a regional medical center
• Improve Sudley Road from Godwin Drive to Grant Avenue for
an attractive gateway and good travel-way
• Encourage higher density professional offi ces and retail space
Similar to the goals and objectives above, this sector plan provides land
use recommendations that defi ne and enhance future development
potential in the sector area and support adjusting the corridor’s existing
framework to accommodate denser, mixed-use development that
respects the hospital’s growing needs, and protects the surrounding
residential neighborhoods. The sector area, as defi ned in the current
plan, is bounded to the north and west by Prince William County, to
the west by Godwin Drive and Rolling Road, to the south by single-
family residential communities, to the north and east by Plantation
Lane and the area surrounding Weir Street, and to the east by the area
surrounding Longstreet Drive, Nelson Park and West Street (Figure
The Sudley Road Sector Plan was developed with the guidance of a
Citizen’s Advisory Committee (CAC), led by City staff, and facilitated
by a group of planning consultants. Members of the CAC included
area residents, business owners, church representatives, hospital
representatives, school representatives, and former and current
Planning Commission representatives. The CAC, in conjunction
with staff and consultant input, helped to defi ne issues in the sector
area, develop and critique proposed land use concepts for the sector
area, and provide ideas for future implementation.
The fi rst step in the planning process for the consultants and City
staff was to understand the CAC’s expectations for the Sudley Road
• Establish green space that is incorporated into the existing
• Buffer commercial areas from residential areas
• Understand the future plans for the hospital and stress its
• Understand the role of Sudley Road as an economic corridor
• Protect the existing single-family, business and school
• Understand the changes that have occurred since the 2002
• Understand the potential for mixed-use development
• Focus concerns as they relate to the study area
• Ensure that planning for the area is strategic and thoughtful
• Address the movement and amount of traffi c affecting the area
• Stress the importance of building and property maintenance
• Determine the need for gateway features and signage
Early in the process, the CAC was also asked to perform a photographic
inventory of the sector area which captured areas of the corridor
that committee members found appealing and areas that they found
unappealing. Through this process, the CAC recognized the physical
and social features that currently defi ne the sector area, and how well
these attributes may or may not respond to future change in the area.
Moving forward, the CAC and a small group of stakeholders took
part in a visioning process, during which participants circled, on maps,
portions of the sector area that they felt are likely to change, areas
that are not likely to change, and areas that are not likely to change
in the future, but should. This exercise helped the CAC to further
defi ne the issues surrounding the existing and future character of the
sector area, and facilitated the development of the following goals
1. Improve safety and accessibility for both pedestrians and
2. Create a boulevard feel along Sudley Road that serves as an
appropriate gateway into the City of Manassas.
3. Create design guidelines for redevelopment that enhance the
visual appeal of the area through future development and
4. Explore ways to minimize the visual impacts of the transmission
5. Encourage mixed-use, Town Center development around the
hospital site, and defi ne appropriate opportunities for increasing
development densities along the Sudley Road corridor.
6. Strengthen the buffer between residential and commercial
7. Minimize the impact of truck traffi c on Sudley Road and its
8. Ensure that all service roads are safe and effi cient.
9. Ensure that the Sector Plan developed for the Sudley Road
corridor works with, and complements, the City’s earlier Sector
Plans (i.e., for Mathis Avenue and Old Town Manassas).
Additionally, transportation analyses of the current conditions,
and future conditions under the proposed land use concepts,
were conducted. These analyses accounted for seven signalized
intersections, pedestrian and bicycle connections, an inventory of
sidewalks, and bus service and ridership within the sector area, as
well as the potential impacts associated with eliminating the service
road in proximity of the Post Offi ce.

page.text: Following the analysis of existing conditions in the sector area, and
the identifi cation of constraints to change and opportunities for
future development, the consultants presented two draft land use
concepts to the CAC; the Boulevard Approach (Figure 2 - Boulevard
Approach) and the Villages Concept (Figure 3 - Villages Concept).
The former concept emphasized concentrating new development
along Sudley Road and upgrading Sudley Road to a “grand boulevard.”
The latter concept addressed smaller, village-type communities, both
on Sudley Road and along the adjoining streets.
Both of these concepts emphasized mixed-use development of
varying intensities. The CAC provided feedback on these concepts,
which the consultants incorporated into the consolidated concept
and presented to the committee in late 2009.
Sudley Road (Route 234 Business) serves as a primary access route
between the City of Manassas and Interstate 66 (I-66), located several
miles north of the City limits (Figure 4 - Existing Circulation). Sudley
Road is a four-lane, divided, arterial road with a raised median that
ranges in width from four feet at intersections with left-turn lanes, to
40 feet at the northern end of the study corridor. The Sudley Road
corridor is a little less than one and a half miles long, and extends
from Godwin Drive to the north, to Grant Avenue to the south.
The segment of Sudley Road within the study area is considered a
principal arterial roadway that serves the Prince William Hospital and
surrounding offi ce, retail and residential land uses.
Other key roadways in the sector area include Godwin Drive, an
arterial roadway that runs along the western boundary of the City
and joins Sudley Road north of the City; major secondary roads:
Stonewall Road and Grant Avenue; and key east-west arteries: Rolling
Road, Digges Road, Plantation Lane, and Stonewall Road. There is
an existing service road along the northbound side of Sudley Road,
just north of Grant Avenue to Plantation Lane. This service road
provides access to the Post Offi ce, as well as to several banks and
offi ces. There are several driveways along both sides of Sudley Road
and along side streets, which serve as access points to various retail,
residential and offi ce uses. More specifi cally, there are ten driveways
in the northbound direction and 19 driveways in the southbound
direction along Sudley Road, from Godwin Drive to Grant Avenue.
Peak hour turning movement counts were collected at seven
signalized intersections, including Sudley Road at Godwin Drive,
Sudley Road at Rolling Road, Sudley Road at Dorsey Circle, Sudley
Road at Plantation Lane, Sudley Road at Stonewall Road, Sudley
Road at Grant Avenue, and Sudley Road at Digges Road. These
turning movement counts were taken between the hours of 6:00 AM
and 9:00 AM, and 4:00 PM and 7:00 PM, during a period of ten days,
from October 21, 2008 to October 30, 2008. Additionally, pedestrian
and bicycle counts were taken across intersection legs. Travel lane
confi gurations at each signalized intersection can be found in the
During both the AM and PM peak hours, through traffi c (non-turning)
was observed moving at free-fl ow speeds in each direction, which
suggests that traffi c signal progression is good. Although traffi c in
each direction of travel on Sudley Road appeared to be relatively
balanced, volumes were slightly higher in the northbound direction
during the AM peak period and in the southbound direction during
the PM peak period. These volumes are likely attributable to the
number of City residents who commute north to I-66 in the morning
and return home in the southbound direction in the evening. The
turning movement count data sheets and a fi gure presenting the AM
and PM peak hour volumes along Sudley Road are both included in
Delays in through traffi c were minor, as a result of good signal
progression in the sector area; however, long delays in through traffi c
were observed along the service road in front of the Post Offi ce, at
the intersection of Sudley and Stonewall Roads.

page.text: During the windshield surveys, signifi cant pedestrian and bicycle
activity was observed along the study corridor, especially in the
vicinity of the hospital and the post offi ce. These observations
were confi rmed by the bicycle and pedestrian intersection counts.
The existing pedestrian facilities conditions at each of the corridor
• An existing on-road bike lane is provided along eastbound
Godwin Drive approaching the Sudley Road intersection.
The intersections of Sudley Road at Hospital Way/Dorsey Circle
and Sudley Road at Stonewall Road contain marked crosswalks
with pedestrian push buttons and pedestrian signal phases.
• The intersection of Sudley Road at Grant Avenue contains
marked crosswalks and pedestrian push buttons.
• The intersection of Sudley Road at Plantation Lane contains
marked crosswalks, but lacks pedestrian push buttons or

at Rolling Road and Sudley Road at Digges Road lack marked

Continuous sidewalks are provided along both sides Sudley Road,
with the exception of a few breaks at locations along the south side
of Sudley Road, from Digges Road to Manassas Baptist School, the
north side of Sudley Road in the southeast quadrant of the Rolling
Road intersection, and between Impalla Drive and Godwin Drive.
The width of the sidewalks along the study corridor appears to be
OmniLink and Cross County Connector buses operated by the
serve the study area. Bus ridership was estimated using the number
of people observed waiting at stops instead of the number of people
on the buses. During the windshield surveys, very few bus riders were
observed waiting at bus stops along the corridor.
On-street parking is not permitted along any portion of Sudley Road
or along any of the cross streets within several hundred feet of the
traffi c signals; however, retail and offi ce uses in the area appear to
provide ample parking. During the windshield survey, it was observed
that the parking lots were not completely occupied during AM or PM
Crash data was provided by the City of Manassas to obtain an
overview of the safety conditions along the corridor. For a period of
three years, from October 1, 2005 through September 30, 2008, a total
of 225 accidents were recorded along Sudley Road, from Godwin
Drive to Grant Avenue. The data shows that the highest number
of crashes occurred at the Grant Avenue intersection, followed by
the Stonewall Road and Plantation Lane intersections, with 33 and
31 accidents, respectively. The majority of accidents were caused by
drivers failing to yield at the right-of-way, typically resulting in angle
or left-turn crashes. The severity of these accidents could not be
All signalized intersections along Sudley Road currently operate
at acceptable levels of service (LOS D or better) during the AM
and PM peak hours, with the exception of the Sudley Road/Grant
Avenue intersection, which operates at LOS E during the PM peak
hour. The detailed signal timing plans for each of the intersections
were provided by the City and are included in the Appendix.
Existing land uses within the sector area generally comprise both
high-density and, low-density residential, neighborhood commercial,
general commercial and semi-public uses, as designated by the City
of Manassas 2002 Comprehensive Land Use Plan.
High-density residential land use is characterized by multi-family
dwellings with no average maximum density. Existing high-
density residential development along the corridor is located in
the northwestern section of the sector area, opposite the hospital
north of Sudley Road. A separate area of high-density residential
development is located in the southwestern section of the corridor,
south of Sudley Road and west of the hospital. Development
surrounding these areas includes commercial uses and residential
uses of a similar, or higher, density.

text.i: Offi ces off of Sudley Road

page.text: Low-density residential land use is characterized by single-family
detached homes on lots of 10,000 square feet or more, with an
average maximum density of 4 units per acre. Areas of low-density
residential development within the sector area are located between
Plantation Lane and Grant Avenue, behind the general offi ce uses
fronting onto Sudley Road, and along the southern side of Sudley
Road, between Stonewall Road and Grant Avenue. Although
designated as low-density residential development, the area abutting
the Canterbury Shopping Center, north of Sudley Road, comprises
townhouse residential development. For the most part, low-density
residential uses in the sector area are surrounded by residential uses
that are similar in scale, with the exception of residential areas that
are closest to commercial development along Sudley Road.
Professional business offi ce land use is characterized by offi ce parks
and centers with multi-story offi ce buildings, which are generally
occupied by professional, business and medical services. Specifi c to
the sector area, the majority of this use comprises hospital-related/
medical support offi ce development. Areas of professional offi ce
development within the sector area front onto the northern side
of Sudley Road, between Plantation Lane and Stonewall Road, and
Rolling Road and Thomas Drive. Similar development fronting on
the southern side of Sudley Road is located between Digges Road
and the Manassas Baptist Church. Development bordering both the
east and west sides of the professional offi ces along the corridor is
generally commercial, while development to the north and south (or
behind) these areas is generally residential. The hospital separates the
professional business uses to the east from the general commercial
General commercial use is characterized by general retail, wholesale
trade activities, auto-related industries and other uses that enhance
the City’s tax base. Areas of general commercial development along
the corridor are located at the western edge of the sector area, south
of Sudley Road and west of the hospital, and on the north side of
Sudley Road, west of Plantation Lane. Development surrounding
these areas is generally of similar commercial use to the east and
west, and residential to north of areas north of Sudley Road and to
the south of areas south of Sudley.
Semi-public land use is characterized by assembly and institutional
development, which generally comprises private schools, hospitals,
nursing homes, churches, and civic uses. The largest areas of semi-
public development within the sector area include the Prince William
Hospital and the Manassas Baptist Church, both south of Sudley
Road. The Manassas Baptist Church property also includes the former
Marsteller School. The Bethel Lutheran Church is located on the
northern side of Sudley Road, opposite the Manassas Baptist Church,
between Plantation Lane and Stonewall Avenue. The Manassas St.
Thomas United Methodist Church is located in the eastern section
of the sector area, north of Sudley Road, west of Grant Avenue, and
east of Forestwood Drive. Development surrounding these areas
ranges from commercial in some locations, to residential in others.
In general, commercial development borders these uses to the east
and west, with residential development to north of areas north of
Sudley Road and to the south of areas south of Sudley.
Existing zoning in the sector area includes B-4 (General Commercial),
B-1 (Professional Business Offi ce), R-5 (Multifamily Residential),
B-4 designations are reserved for a wide array of retail, offi ce, service
and institutional uses that serve both local and nonlocal patrons, with
a maximum building height of 55 feet. Areas along the corridor
that are designated B-4 include a portion of the hospital property,
the commercial area west of Rolling Road on the southern side
of Sudley Road, and the commercial area west of Plantation Lane
north of Sudley Road. B-1 designations are reserved for offi ce
development with limited retail and institutional uses, that serves
as a transition between nearby residential developments and higher
intensity nonresidential uses. The maximum building height of B-1
development is 55 feet. B-1 zoning designations are located within
and around the hospital property, south of Sudley Road and east of
Rolling Road, and east of the former Marstellar School site.
The former Marsteller Middle School, opposite Plantation Lane on
the west side of Sudley Road, was purchased by the Manassas Baptist
Church from Prince William County in 2002. After the purchase,
the land was rezoned to B-4 (General Commercial) for use as an
adult care facility, afterschool facility, and as leased offi ce space to the
hospital. The B-4 zoning designation is heavily proffered to restrict
use and activities on the site, but it does permit fl exible uses, such as
those above, for the benefi t of the church and adjacent professional
R-5 designations are reserved for multifamily dwellings, with
a maximum building height of 45 feet. Areas zoned for R-5
development along the corridor are located west of Rolling Road,
south of Sudley Road; and west of Plantation Lane, north of Sudley
Road. Both areas are behind the B-4 designations fronting onto
Sudley Road. All remaining land in the sector area is zoned R-1. R-1
designations are reserved for detached, single-family homes at a low
suburban density of approximately three dwelling units per acre or
less, with a maximum building height of 35 feet.
Southwest of the sector area, land is generally zoned R-2S (Single-
Family Residential), and land to the southeast of the sector area is
generally zoned R-1. R-2S designations are reserved for detached,
single-family homes at a high suburban density of approximately 4.3
dwelling units per acre or less, with a maximum building height of
35 feet. Northwest of the sector area, land is generally zoned R-7
(Planned Residential) with a small pocket of A-1 (Agricultural). R-7
designations are reserved for organized residential developments
with appropriate supportive community facilities and services, with
a maximum height of 35 feet, with the exception of age-restricted
housing. A-1 designations are reserved for limited agricultural
activities and detached single-family residential development at an
extremely low density (1 DU/acre), with a maximum building height
The western edge of the corridor, located at the intersection of Sudley
Road and Godwin Drive, marks the departure from Prince William
County and the entry into the City of Manassas. The transition in
development is fairly smooth, and refl ective of existing development
to the west, in Prince William County. The eastern edge of the
corridor is distinguished by Nelson Park, at the intersection of Sudley
Road and Grant Avenue. The transition in development character in
the eastern section of the corridor is less smooth than in the western
section, shifting from suburban commercial development along
Sudley Road to older, established residential neighborhoods along
Grant Avenue. This edge of the corridor also serves as an artery to
Development in the sector area is generally of a suburban scale,
comprising single-use, one- to two-story buildings surrounded by
surface parking, which separates the buildings’ edge from Sudley
Road. These large setbacks create an environment that is very
auto-dependant and can be considered a deterrent to pedestrian
accessibility along the corridor. Additionally, the inconsistent
and intermittent network of sidewalks in the sector area does not
promote or encourage pedestrian circulation, nor does the absence
of pedestrian connections to the surrounding residential areas. The
style of development within the sector area is generally inconsistent
and can be described as a mixture of suburban retail, offi ce park and
The Prince William Hospital, a dominant landholder in the sector
area, comprises a series of buildings that vary in height from one to
four fl oors, with large areas of surface parking. In the absence of a
Master Plan for the hospital site, Manassas planning staff analyzed
several other Novant hospital sites in order to understand what ideas
Novant might have for the Prince William Hospital site. This analysis
Additionally, the Manassas Baptist Church comprises the majority of
the southeastern section of the corridor, and is set back from Sudley
Road by a large area of green space. Other dominant landholders in
the sector area include the Post Offi ce and several other churches.
The CAC felt that the lack of cohesive development north of Sudley
Road is of concern, as are the presence of overhead power lines, the
number of vacant buildings, and the lack of an attractive, welcoming
gateway into the City of Manassas in the sector area. Of additional
concern is the absence of development that complements the
pedestrian environment, the lack of businesses fronting onto Sudley
Road, the predominance of single-use development, the separation
of uses by large surface parking lots, the lack of cohesion and
connectedness of development in the sector area with surrounding
development, and the lack of open space.
The sector area is located within the Flat Branch watershed, which
is a tributary of Bull Run, and lies within two 100-year fl oodplains.
One fl oodplain parallels Sudley Road and runs behind Digges Road,
through Peabody Street and Stonewall Road, and follows Beauregard
Avenue west of Sudley Road. The other fl oodplain runs east of
Sudley Road and crosses Stonewall Road and Grant Avenue, behind
A 2008 spatial analysis of the City’s existing tree canopy indicates
that the sector area has a minimal amount of tree cover and a large
The sector area contains a minimal amount of open space, most
of which is passive. Nelson Park is the only dedicated park in the
sector area, and is located at 8915 Grant Avenue, on the corner of
Grant Avenue and Sudley Road. The park sits on approximately two
acres and includes a wooden gazebo, benches, picnic tables and a
water fountain. Long-term plans for Nelson Park include relocating
and constructing a new gazebo and fountain. The Prince William
Hospital owns a large tract of land which is currently planted with
pine trees. This parcel of land includes the remains of a sewage
treatment plant as well as a stream, which appears to be severely
impacted by the eroding stream bank. Additionally, the Manassas
Baptist Church owns a large amount of green space along the rear
Civic features within the sector area include the Haydon Elementary
School, located directly behind the hospital property, and the
Post Offi ce. Haydon Elementary underwent a recent addition and
renovation that increased capacity for the 2007/2008 school year.
Physical constraints to controlled, vehicular access in the sector area
include the service road that connects Plantation Lane and Stonewall
Road, the truck traffi c that uses Stonewall Road as a cut-through to
avoid Sudley Road, and the volume of traffi c on Sudley Road. The
Post Offi ce, located on the service road, generates a high volume of
traffi c which causes long delays in traffi c at the intersection of Sudley
Road and Stonewall Road, as well as traffi c entering and exiting
the Post Offi ce via Sudley Road. Since the majority of lane uses
along Stonewall Road are residential, the truck traffi c through these
residential areas is a general nuisance and could be a potential safety
risk. Additionally, the amount and frequency of traffi c on Sudley
Road are constraints to tying together both sides of the corridor, and
to identifying appropriate uses along this active/high-traffi c corridor.
Another physical constraint is the Prince William Hospital, which
was recently acquired by Novant Health. At this time, the hospital
has announced preliminary plans for expanded services. Hospital
management is still in the process of conducting its own master
planning study; however, future plans for the hospital are unknown
at this time. This sector plan presents guidelines for future hospital
development to allow the hospital to continue its role as a good
neighbor within the sector area, and provides the hospital with
fl exibility to work within an urban framework that is guided by these
The issue regarding the hospital’s stake in the community was fi rst
and foremost among the list of issues generated by the CAC and
stakeholders. This issue led to many discussions with the CAC and
other community stakeholders about the future identity of the sector
area. Other issues and concerns included the following:
• Traffi c ingress and egress from the Sudley Road Post Offi ce is
very diffi cult and is often exacerbated by traffi c congestion on
• Many people use the parking lots of churches within the study
area for cut-through access and turnaround space.
• The change in nature and character of development from the
north end of the sector boundary to the City boundary to the
A majority of churches within the study area would like to expand
their services and facilities to meet the needs of their growing
congregations, and to accommodate other public uses.
• The perception that traffi c on Stonewall Road, generated by
schools and churches to the south, is worsening.
• The sector area lacks continuous sidewalks along Sudley Road
• Signalized timing at intersections along Sudley Road is often too
short to cross this road safely.
• There is a desire for more pedestrian mobility in the study area.
• Many people would like more upscale restaurants along Sudley
• As development in the area occurs, additional buffers will be
needed between residential and commercial development.
The preference for vertical development would be for a structure
lower, rather than higher, in height.
• Many drivers, especially truck drivers, use the secondary roads
surrounding Sudley Road to bypass Sudley Road.
• The City is losing residents and congregations to the Haymarket
• There is a desire for the sector to grow commercially, but for
new development to respect and retain the existing residential
Mixed-use development would be welcome on Sudley Road if it is
compatible with/buffered from adjacent residential communities.
As a “homework” assignment, the CAC was asked to develop a vision
statement for the sector area. The vision statement presented to the
group by committee member Tina Cox was unanimously accepted by
her fellow CAC members as the offi cial vision statement for the plan.

area in ten years, the CAC responded with the following:
• A charming, vital area that incorporates a healthy and vibrant
